e group of citizens. This book fills this gap, by exploring how diverse citizens experience welfare provision. It aims to promote debate about the importance of social divisions in society and to address the gaps in research, in relation to race, ethnicity, disability, gender and LGBTQ+. It comes at a crucial time as we emerge out of a decade of austerity, a global pandemic and Brexit, where issues of diversity have been at the forefront of debates, and renews the call for analysis within social policy, particularly on issues of diversity in the 21st century context.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCultural pluralismzGreat Britain. 0aEqualityzGreat Britain. 0aMarginality, SocialzGreat Britain. 0aPublic welfarezGreat Britain. 0aSocial servicezGreat Britain. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Policy.2bisacsh1 aBeck, Dave, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBentley, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrew, Teresa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngland, Edith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEseonu, Temidayo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarcia, Gerardo Javier Arriaga, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrant, Aimee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGregory, Lee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGregory, Lee, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGwilym, Hefin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIafrati, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIafrati, Steve, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKa